<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Johnny’s Is the Best Overall Choice</h2>

  <p>
    Johnny’s Selected Seeds stands out because it makes maturity timing usable, not just visible.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is especially helpful for:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>comparing early, mid, and late varieties of the same crop</li>
    <li>building staggered planting schedules</li>
    <li>adjusting timing based on your available growing window</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This makes it much easier to plan a sequence instead of guessing when to replant.
  </p>

  <p>
    It also helps you combine faster and slower crops intentionally, especially when working with <a href="/guides/best-seed-company-for-fast-maturing-varieties/">fast-maturing varieties</a> to keep harvests moving.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why High Mowing Works Well for Repeated Plantings</h2>

  <p>
    High Mowing Organic Seeds is a strong option when consistency matters more than precision.
  </p>

  <p>
    Its varieties tend to:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>germinate reliably across multiple sowings</li>
    <li>perform consistently under changing conditions</li>
    <li>focus on productive, practical crops</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This is especially useful when planting the same crop several times and expecting similar results each round.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When West Coast Seeds Is the Better Fit</h2>

  <p>
    West Coast Seeds becomes more useful when your growing season limits how many successions you can fit.
  </p>

  <p>
    It works best for:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>cooler climates with slower crop development</li>
    <li>shorter seasons where timing margins are tighter</li>
    <li>gardens where not all plantings will finish reliably</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In these conditions, choosing varieties that can complete their cycle on time becomes more important than maximizing the number of plantings.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Actually Makes Succession Planting Work</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Clear maturity timing.</strong> You need to know how long each crop takes so you can plan the next one.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Reliable germination.</strong> Each planting needs to establish quickly to keep the cycle moving.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Good crop pairing.</strong> Some crops naturally follow others better in the same space.
  </p>

  <p>
    A good seed company supports these decisions instead of leaving you to estimate them.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Succession Plans Often Break Down</h2>

  <p>
    Most issues come from timing slipping over the season.
  </p>

  <p>
    This happens when:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>crops take longer than expected to mature</li>
    <li>replanting is delayed after harvest</li>
    <li>later plantings do not finish before conditions change</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These problems tend to compound as the season progresses.
  </p>

  <p>
    That is why it helps to understand <a href="/guides/will-my-crop-mature-before-first-frost/">whether later plantings will mature before the first frost</a> so your full sequence stays intact.
  </p>
</section>

